@node M_CONVMODE "Conversion modes"

    @{u}Conversion modes@{uu}

Three different types of conversion can be performed, depending on
the mode selected.

Whatever method is used, the first track of the output MIDI
file has the name of the song and contains only tempo changes,
system exclusive messages, and various text events, if any.

The default conversion is the SMART one:
    it creates a file with one track for each MIDI instrument
    used in the song plus the song track above mentioned.
    This is the default mode.

The second conversion type is DIRECT:
    it builds a track for each song block track (this version
    supports up to 32 tracks per block).
    Actually, the real "original" MMD1 format supported only
    4,8,12 or 16 tracks per block, but, since the format can allow
    ANY number of tracks, the newer releases of OctaMED and
    SoundStudio removed this restriction.

    So, be aware that the older module players available can only
    work right with older MMD1 modules, that have only 4-8-12-16
    tracks per block, but MID-It! doesn't have this limit.

    The direct conversion generates a file in which the events are
    played in exactly the same order as in the OctaMED playroutine
    (note by note, command by command).

The third - and last - conversion mode is the CHANNEL one;
    it features one track for each MIDI channel; that is, if you use
    in a module more instruments that share the same MIDI channel,
    their events will be inserted in the same MIDI file track.

Smart conversion is better (I think is is more clever to have
each instrument data in a separate track) but notes will be
played in a different order than on OctaMED - actually, the real
playing order depends from the player routine used.
The same applies to Channel conversion.

This fact, especially when your music gets near to the maximum
polyphonic power of your MIDI machines, can make substantial
differences when listening to the output MIDI file, causing
'cutted' and 'delayed' notes and other unpleasant effects for our
ears.

Should this happen, you can change the arrangement of tracks to
change the event playing order.
You should do it easily using a MIDI sequencer (my hint is: put
first the rhythm instrument tracks).

@endnode


@node M_CONVOPT "Conversion options"

    @{u}Conversion options@{uu}

    'Running status': default for this one is on in the MUI
        version and off in the CLI one (this difference exists
        only to keep option compatibility with the v1 MID-It).
        When on, the output file is built using a special data
        compression system used right for MIDI files.
        Actually, there should be no reason for turning it
        off, since the running status compression is a MIDI
        file specification, so every MIDI program should be
        able to deal with it.

        Furthermore, some sequencers (on the Mac computer
        especially) have been reported to hang when loading
        a MIDI file obtained with this option turned off.

        Try disabling running status only if the sequencer
        you use does not seem to appreciate the files produced
        when it is set to on.

    'Use note off': by default, the sequence used for turning
        off a note is using a Note On message with velocity 0,
        the very same thing done when OctaMED plays a song.
        If you wish to use instead Note Off messages (with
        fixed velocity of 127) just enable this feature.
        Please note that, because of the running status data
        compression system, if you use this option together
        with the running status, the MIDI file produced will
        be quite bigger.
        Instead, if you don't specify running status, the file
        length should be exactly the same either using Note On
        or Off.

    'Block names': if this is on and you have used block names
        - a feature not present on MMD0 modules - they will be
        inserted in the track 0 of the output MIDI file, as text
        events, when each block data starts to be played.
        This could be handy for kara-oke implementation and
        other tricky and funny things, I hope :)

    'End shut': this causes the converter to shut all hanging
        notes when the module ends (this way it can be played
        in loop without notes staying across).

    'No warnings': if you want to avoid any warning message,
        just turn it on. Please note that you do it at your
        own risk, because the conversion could be faulty and
        you could not be aware of it; you'd better be sure that
        your module is safe before using this switch, for example
        if you need to convert again a module that you KNOW is OK.

    'Empty beats': you can specify any number between 0 and 16.
        An empty time corresponding to the amount of beats chosen
        will be inserted at the beginning of the MIDI file.
        This feature can be useful, for example, to insert at a
        later time some MIDI initialization data before the real
        song data starts.

@endnode


@node M_USAGE "The MUI version"

    @{u}The MUI version@{uu}

Starting from V2, MID-It offers a complete MUI front-end that allows
performing all operations without having to type anything (unless you
want to change the output filename).

Indeed, the MUI MID-It! features a window containing everything is
needed to perform the needed song conversions and to set all the
desired options.

Most of these settings can also be initialized to the desired
values using the @{" startup arguments " link M_TEMPLATE }.

It is a good thing to read these part of the documentation by
having the MID-It! window opened somewhere, so that you can
quickly see what I am writing about just while you read it.

Starting from the upper left corner of the window, you can find
two buttons, the first (showing a question mark) calling the about
requester and the second (showing a 'I') causing the application to
get iconified.

The big string gadget on the right of the two buttons allows to
insert the name of the module to be loaded, operation that can
more comfortably performed by clicking the requester pop up
button lying at the right side of the string gadget.
Pressing the pop up button, guess what, makes an ASL file
requester suddenly show up.
Once inserted the name, or selected the file from the ASL
requester, the module is loaded.
This should normally be the first operation, though it
is also possible to set the conversion options even before
loading.
Starting from v2.6, if the inserted string is ending in ':'
or '/' it is considered as a default path for the loading requester.
While this little feature is not very useful here, it is instead
when you start the MUI MID-It giving a path only @{" NAME " link M_TEMPLATE }.

The second row of the user interface is taken by the song
selector: if your module is a multisong one, you can use this
section to browse the songs in it until selecting the one you
plan to convert, just by moving the slider on the right side.
The number presented on the right of the slider shows the number of
songs contained in the loaded module (new from V2.8).
The name of the currently selected song appears in the text
box on the left.

The window is then divided in four framed groups, reflecting
from left to right the order of the various parts of the
conversion process:

    @{" MMD Info " link M_MMDINFO }

    @{" Mode " link M_MODE }

    @{" Options " link M_OPTIONS }

    @{" MID Info " link M_MIDINFO }

Below these items, there are three buttons on the same row:

    - 'Open' just pops up the "load file" requester.

    - 'Convert!' starts the conversion of the loaded module using
      the current option settings.
      Once the process has started, you can still change the
      options but the operation in progress won't be affected by
      such selections.
      Besides, the button label changes to 'Abort' and the
      elaboration can be interrupted by pressing it again.
      When a conversion is aborted, all data produced in the
      meanwhile is erased - the partial results of an unfinished
      conversion are never kept.

    - 'Save' pops up a requester to save the converted MID file
      wherever needed.
      The default filename is equal to the input, with some little
      changes: any trailing or leading .med, .mod, .omed, med.,
      mod. and omed. are removed and .MID is appended at the end.
      To improve Powerpacker and XPK compatibility, also trailing
      '.pp' and '.xpk' are cut when creating the output filename.
      A requester is activated if the chosen file already exists,
      so you have to confirm if you want to overwrite it.

The last item left to describe is the status line, reporting the
various steps of the current operation.

@endnode

@node M_MMDINFO "The MMD information display"

    @{u}MMD information display@{uu}

The MMD info information box shows various
informations about the module currently loaded.
Here are the voices and their meaning:

    - 'Format' is the format of the module; as of current release,
       only MMD0 or MMD1 formats are handled correctly; you simply
       cannot use MMD2 and higher with MID-It.

 (*)- 'Timing' is the timing system used for the song:
      can be one of BPM or SPD.

    - 'Instruments' is the number of the last instrument used in the
       whole module. Actually, the song can use a subset of all the
       module instruments.
       In this situation, when smart/channel mode is selected, only tracks
       for the actually used instruments/channels are generated.

 (*)- 'Len' is the playing sequence len, in other words how many
      blocks are played one after the other during the song.

 (*)- 'Blocks' is the total number of blocks for the song.
      Actually, the playing sequence can use a subset of them, but
      this does not make any difference.

    - 'Bytes' is the byte len of the whole module.

The items tagged with (*) are song dependent, thus their content can
be different for each song of a multisong module.

@endnode

@node M_MODE "Mode setup"

    @{u}Conversion mode selector@{uu}

Use this cycle gadget to choose the preferred @{" conversion mode " link M_CONVMODE }.

@endnode

@node M_OPTIONS "Options setup"

    @{u}Conversion options setup@{uu}

Using this box, you can set up your own favourite @{" settings " link M_CONVOPT }
for the song conversion.

@endnode

@node M_MIDINFO "The MID information display"

    @{u}MID information display@{uu}

This display box is filled with data after the first pass of
the conversion - data analysis - has been completed.

These are the voices and their meaning:

    - 'Division' is the number of clock ticks for each beat
      of the song. This release of MID-It! tries to associate
      to every OctaMED timer tick eight MIDI clock ticks,
      but if the resulting 'division' is bigger than 384, this
      ratio is halved till the division comes to a value less or
      equal than 384. I put this limit because I think that a MIDI
      resolution of 384 ticks per beat is more than enough for
      everyday use, and more could make the song play too much
      "CPU-Loader". If you need greater division, just contact @{" me " link M_AUTHOR }.

    - 'Play time' is the duration, in minutes and second, of
      the converted song, excluding any user selected
      @{" empty beats " link M_CONVOPT }.

    - 'Tracks' is the total number of tracks contained in the
      MIDI file being created.

    - 'Bytes' is the total byte len of the MIDI file being
      created.

@endnode


@node M_TEMPLATE "Startup arguments"

    @{u}Startup arguments@{uu}

Even if everything in MID-It! can now handled using a true GUI,
all the conversion options can be set to the desired value from
startup using various parameters (when invoked from a CLI) or
tooltypes (if started from Workbench).

Before going on reading, you'd better be familiar with the
program conversion @{" modes " link M_CONVMODE } and @{" options " link M_CONVOPT }.

The command line template is:

    midit NAME, NORSTATUS/S, USENOTEOFF/S, BLOCKNAMES/S, ENDSHUT/S,
          QUIET/S, EMPTYBEATS/N/K, CONVMODE/N/K"

    - NAME must be followed by the complete name (with path), of a
      module to be loaded as soon as the program starts.
      Starting from version 2.6, if only a path ending with ":" or
      "/" is specified, it is taken as the default path for the ASL
      load requester.

    - NORSTATUS disables the running status option.

    - USENOTEOFF, BLOCKNAMES, ENDSHUT, QUIET enable the
      corresponding option.

    - EMPTYBEATS must be followed by a number which will be clipped
      in the range 0-16, and will be the default 'empty beats' value.

    - CONVMODE must be followed by a number, and allows to select
      the default conversion mode:

        0 is SMART conversion

        1 is DIRECT conversion

        2 is CHANNEL conversion

The tooltypes are exactly the same, except for the fact that the
boolean (/S) options must have value "TRUE" to be enabled; any other
value specified will disable them.

Tooltype example: NORSTATUS=TRUE (disables running status)

@endnode


@node M_WORKBENCH "Workbench and MID-It!"

    @{u}Workbench support@{uu}

Version 2.8 introduces some features that make MID-It! much more
handy from within the workbench environment.

The first of them is the use of tooltypes, that have been explained
in the previous section; they make it possibile to set/reset options
at startup using the parameters contained in the program icon.

Another useful add-on is the app-window: dragging the icon of a
module over the program main window causes the module to be loaded
and made ready for conversion.

The very same behaviour can be obtained when MID-It is iconified by
dragging a module icon over the program (app-)icon.

If an icon has MID-It set as the default tool, when double clicked
it will start MID-It that will try to load the file that the selected
icon belongs to. Furthermore, if the module icon has tooltypes for
the conversion settings, they will be used; this makes it possible,
for example to set different options for each module!

Anyway, if multifile selection is used, only the first selected file
is considered.

@endnode


@node M_CLIWHY "Why another CLI MID-It!"

    @{u}The reasons for supporting again CLI MID-It!@{uu}

This somehow reduced edition of MID-It! is still included for a
number of reasons:

    - First, not all people likes MUI, and not everybody has gone
      to kickstart 2 and upper, but MID-It! can work well even with
      a stock 512k Amiga 1000 - I strongly hope so since I don't own
      any - so maybe someone could still need this version, taking
      advantage of the newer features.

    - Second, you can process lots of modules in sequence only by
      using this version with its wildcard handling capabilities;
      watch out the @{" Program usage " link M_CLIUSAGE } for further details.

    - Third and last, being this no less no more than a CLI command,
      it can be easily driven by a good file manager like Directory
      Opus and Disk Master.

The main differences (good and bad) from the full MID-It are:

    - No MUI, so no graphic user interface
    - No Workbench support
    - Should work on any kickstart from V33 to V42(??)
    - Can process several files in one pass thanx to wildcard
      scanning capability
    - Requires less resources, so it's shorter and needs less
      memory too :)

When present, locale data is used for this version too.

@endnode


@node M_CLIUSAGE "CLI MID-It! usage"

    @{u}CLI MID-It! arguments@{uu}

    Usage is: cli_midit <options> <input file> <output file>

If you need some 'mental refresh' about the option letters, just
type 'cli_midit' with no parameters.

If <output file> is not specified, it will be <input file>,
modified as follows:

    - any leading "mod.", ".omed" or "med." is removed
    - any trailing ".mod" , ".omed" or ".med", ".pp" or ".xpk"
      is removed
    - extension ".MID" is appended to the filename

You can also specify only a path destination without filename.

Valid examples are:

  cli_midit -b -r ram:module
      @{i}no output file specified, it will be ram:module.MID@{ui}

  cli_midit -b -r -e -q ram:module ram:convmodule
      @{i}output file is ram:convmodule (no .MID appended)@{ui}

  cli_midit -breq ram:module ram:convmodule
      @{i}same as previous, just show the option grouping ability@{ui}

  cli_midit -r ram:med.#? RAM:sound/
      @{i}Convert all modules in ram: beginning with med., save
      them to the directory ram:sound, (.MID is appended since
      no output file name is supplied)@{ui}

Please note the slash at the end of the last example: it must
ALWAYS be present if you specify a destination subdirectory
without destination filename, otherwise no output file will be
produced.

AmigaDOS wildcards "#?" can be used in the input filename to
convert several modules with a single command line, and a special
option (-u) is present to activate Unix and MS-DOS "*?" wildcards,
excluding the AmigaDOS ones.
No wildcards are allowed in the destination filename.

PLEASE NOTE: If you specify wildcards for input and a filename
for output, the destination filename will be overwritten and only
the last converted song will be contained in it.

The options are the same as the new MUI version, plus the
'addtime' (-s) one that I have left here only for compatibility
purposes but which I consider quite useless.


    @{u}Options@{uu}

    @{"Conversion mode" link M_CONVMODE } (default = SMART):

    -d:  use DIRECT conversion

    -c:  use CHANNEL conversion


    @{"Conversion options" link M_CONVOPT }

    -n:  use note off messages

    -r:  use running status

    -t:  shut notes at end of song

    -b:  use block names

    -e[number]:  if followed by a number in the range 1 to 16 it
                 is taken as the number of empty beats to be put
                 before the song starts.

                 If no number follows it means 4 empty beats (just
                 like in the previous releases)

    -m<number>:  allows to select the song to be converted inside
                 a multimodule. Number starts from 1 for the first song.
                 Only one song per module can be converted by one call
                 to MID-It!.

    -s<number>:  can be used to change the playing speed of your song:
                 when activated the file resulting from the conversion
                 contains tempo events which values are different from
                 the original ones: the time factor specified after the
                 -s option is added to the actual bpm value of each song
                 tempo event.
                 For example -s2 causes the resulting midi song to be 2
                 beats per minute faster than the input song (-s-2 would
                 produce a slower song instead).
                 Each and every tempo change event is altered, and
                 the resulting values are clipped in the range 1-240
                 beats per minute.


    Misc options:

    -p:  (NO LONGER WORKS) was used to suppress the conversion
         progress status line. You can specify it, but it won't
         work. This was made to allow old command lines still work.

    -u:  enables Unix/MS-DOS wildcards (*?) instead of the AmigaDOS
         ones.  This is for who is used to such systems or for
         converting a module which name contains the character # (the
         symbol ? is a wildcard in Unix too).

    -q:  enables quiet mode, suppressing any warning that can be
         produced.
         BE CAREFUL: if you suppress warnings you make it at your
         own risk, because the conversion could be faulty and you
         could not be aware of it; you'd better be sure that your
         module is 'solid' before using this switch.

Please note that when using one option that needs a numeric
argument, this one must follow close (with no spaces) to the
option letter and, if there are other options to be specified,
they have to be separately supplied.
I mean:

    options to convert a module using direct conversion
    and running status:

    -s3dr       Wrong: options 'd' and 'r' are ignored.
    -s 3 -dr    Wrong: the 3 should immediately follow the s.

    -s3 -dr     Correct
    -drs3       Correct

I hope these examples were clear enough...

@endnode


@node M_RESTREQ "Requirements and restrictions"

    @{u}Requirements@{uu}

From version 2.8b, medplayer.library is no longer requested to load
modules - MID-It can now work without need of external (non system)
libraries.

To be able to import crunched modules you need powerpacker.library
for PowerPacker'ed files (minimum version: 35) and xpkmaster.library
(minimum version: 2) for the XPK packed files (of course, you need
the right compressor sublibs too).

Please note that if you use PowerPacker'ed encrypted files,
reqtools.library must be installed in your system; otherwise
the decrypt password requester won't show and loading will fail.

If having problems with the conversion, try looking at
@{" Known problems " link M_TROUBLES }

Due to the MUI front-end and the advanced shell/workbench features,
the full MID-It! needs kickstart 2.0 (V37) or higher to work.
The MUI release used for developement is V3.3-3.8, you are
advised to get the latest MUI release on Aminet and install it
if the program refuses to start.

On the other side, as already mentioned somewhere in this manual,
the CLI version should not need any particular Amiga or kickstart
version to run, and the conversions made with it are perfectly
equal to those performed by the full program.


    @{u}Restrictions@{uu}

The current version has some limitations:

 - Modules must be MMD0 or MMD1 type; these two module formats
   can be produced by all OctaMED and SoundStudio releases, and
   the MED newer versions, too, have the ability to save using the
   MMD0 format.
   If you use OctaMED 5 or higher or SoundStudio, you can save your
   module using MMD0 or MMD1 format, but be careful that your music
   piece does not use any of the extra features offered by MMD2/3
   format (refer to the tracker documentation), otherwise you could
   could loose some important data if you save it using MMD0-1.

 - Modules should not contain any Amiga instruments (only MIDI
   stuff is allowed here!)

 - Modules should contain supplementary info - instrument names
   and similar things- so make sure to save them using the right
   save settings before submitting your music to MID-It!.

 - Track volumes (ie the ones in the "volume" window of newer
   OctaMED and SoundStudio releases) and MIDI extended presets
   are not - yet - supported.

 - Only the "Standard (MSB)" message type is supported in command
   3xnn: all other messages produce a warning and won't be converted.

@endnode


@node M_TIPS "Tips and tricks"

    @{u}Tips and tricks@{uu}

If you use Amiga samples in your modules (together with MIDI or
alone) the modules won't be convertible.

There is a little workaround though: if you assign from OctaMED
a MIDI channel to every non MIDI instrument (thus promoting it
to MIDI), the module will be converted.
Simply, don't expect a perfect conversion: notes will have to be
transposed some octaves up and effects like pitchbend will sound
awful if you try to play the module through a MIDI device.
There is too much difference between Amiga and common MIDI sound
hardware to map in a simple way sound handling from one to the
other.  At least, with little work, you can get a MIDI file
containing all note events of your non MIDI instruments too.
This until a version fully supporting Amiga samples comes up, I
don't know when and even if it will (see @{" notes " link M_DEVNOTES }).

For BPM modules, one thing is worth of being explained.
The slider at the right of the BPM one in the Tempo section
of your MMD tracker - I'm gonna call it "Resolution" from now on
- is intended as a 'slots per beat' indication.

That is, if you set resolution to 8, then 8 block lines are
intended to form a metronome beat. Keep it in mind if your
converted file sounds at different speeds than the original,
or if your sequencer metronome is not synchronized with song.
By now, I still haven't found a way to understand the signature
of an OctaMED song (how to find that a song has a 12/8 tempo??).
Because of this every MIDI file generated contains a 4/4
signature setting.

HINT: OctaMED 5+ has an hidden (undocumented on V5) command,
17xx, that writes directly byte xx into controller 7 (mostly
used for MIDI volume control).  I don't know if older versions
support it too, so, if you think that it could be useful for
you, just try it!!!

@endnode


@node M_TROUBLES "Known problems"

    @{u}Known problems using MID-It!@{uu}


    REPEATED MESSAGES
    -----------------
The warning messages appear always two times - one in the analysis
stage, the second while making the actual conversion. This is not a
real problem, and the bare truth is that I haven't spent very much
time to figure out how to avoid this; in fact, if you notice some
warning produced by some of your modules, you should modify them
until they disappear; if not, MID-It could make anyway a perfect
conversion, but I certainly would not bet about it :*


    SONG LOOPS
    ----------
If you use in your songs commands like the so named pattern break
or song position jump to leap back in the song, a warn message is
produced; if the warning is skipped, the conversion will avoid the
jump back and go on after.
This means that only the first "loop iteration" will be considered.
It is anyway recommended that you prevent such a tricky situation by
preparing your songs so that they have always a real end before
submitting them to conversion.

@endnode


@node M_DEVNOTES "Developement notes"

    @{u}Developement and technical notes@{uu}

I have been putting all efforts to make the program bug free and
easy to use, but even if this is not a big project there are so many
features involved and particular conditions that can elude the
bravest beta tester (they are just men :)).

So you too can participate to make the program more and more solid
and functional (and you are strongly invited to do so); you can also
help me if you wish to prepare the localization for a language that's
missing, or make some nice icon for the project, since I am not very
much prepared for this kind of work.

For any questions/notes/reports about strange behaviour or conversion
mistakes, please contact @{" me " link M_AUTHOR }.

Almost all the MIDI features of a MMD module are fully converted
except for the ones already mentioned in the @{" restrictions " link M_RESTREQ } section.
Furthermore, I had to leave out some very special features that
depend upon the tracker environment; these are the commands,
introduced from OctaMED 6 and SoundStudio, for that trigger external
commands or Arexx scripts and command FF7, that waits for all sys-ex
messages to be sent.

You can find in @{" program history " link M_HISTORY } the list of last things
added, so be aware that these features are obviously the less
tested.

MID-It will be developed as long as I need to do it, or I receive
enough feedback in that direction, or simply to improve my knowledge
of the wonderful Amiga programming world.
This means simply that every new release could be the last.

Here are some things that could be considered like a 'To do if I
think I need them and have enough time' list:

    - Installer script to make installation and update even easier.

    - Complete Rexx interface to perform automatic file processing.

    - Improve MUI implementation (menus, preferences and so on).

    - MMD2/3 format handling?
      I could have already added MMD2 support but, as far as I know,
      this format has never really become of real use, and maybe it
      could cost me more time and efforts than it's worth.

    - Configuration file for options

Please don't ask to add complete Amiga samples support -
or ask it all together, so that I can't say no.

Sure, it would be a great result, but I think I can't get it all by
myself in a short time (and I think it's better that people reach
the MIDI world, as soon as possible).
If the Amiga tracker guys can get so much from 4 poor (even if
beautifully programmable) 8 bit audio channels, God only knows what
we can expect from them when they cross the bridge to real sound!!!
Besides that, consider that most internal audio commands, like
pitchbend, are really difficult to convert to MIDI, because they
depend on a huge number of factors outside the module itself (MIDI
device used, voice settings and so on).

Anyway, while updating MID-It, I found out that maybe one of its main
use can be helping people to perpetuate the tons of great musical
stuff that people have made so far on the Amiga (at least with MIDI).
The Amiga platform is always the best IMHO (at least for programmers),
but it is getting older and older, and as time passes by it is more
and more difficult not to fall into the market groove that keeps it
out of the limelight.
Unless someone really succeeds in bringing it back to the glory
that Amiga absolutely deserves, who knows how long will the MMD
(and ProTracker) format last? I think the MID format will survive
them, even if unfortunately it carries almost no timbric
information.

Developement and testing of MID-It V2 was made by me on the
following setup:

    - Amiga 1200 + 28 MHz68030 + 4MB FAST RAM + 120MB HD

    - Kickstart 39.106, Workbench 40.42

    - MUI 3.8 (*)

    - GoldEd 4.7 and ProgEd 2.4 (each one better than the other) (*)

    - OctaMED 5 (*) , 6, SoundStudio 1.0 (beta)

    - powerpacker.library 36.10 (*)

    - xpkmaster.library 4.12 (*)

    - Midi synth Yamaha SY-85, Roland JV-1080

 (*) = Available for download on Aminet sites

MID-It V2, both MUI and CLI version, is less than 100k standard
C sources, compiled and linked by the great SAS 6.57 environment.

@endnode


